n":{"1335–ABT 1413":"1335–about 1413","1335–1413":"1335–1413","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1395–Male":"1395–Deceased","1285–1340":"1285–1340","1285–Female":"1285–Deceased","1337":"1337","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","ABT 1413":"about 1413","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1340 to 1351":"from 1340 to 1351","about 1340":"about 1340","Hele, Devon, England":"Hele, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Hele, Bradninch, Devon, England":"Hele, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hele","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Heal  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Heal","meanings":["English:","topographic or habitational name for someone who lived in or by a nook or hollow, or at a place called with this word (from Middle English <i>hele</i>, Old English <i>heale</i>, dative singular of <i>healh</i> ‘nook or hollow’). Hele in Somerset derives from this word, but the surname arises chiefly from one or more of the many minor localities named Heal(e) or Hele in Devon. In southwestern England and Kent this is an equivalent of   Hale  .","in the southeast Midlands of England, perhaps a variant of   Hell   1."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":2,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":47,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Hele was born in 1335, in Devon, England, his father, Sir Roger Hele Knight of Hele, was 51 and his mother, Isabel Atwater, was 50. He had at least 1 son with Isabel De Water. He died about 1413, in Hele, Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 79."},"et":{"1335–ABT 1413":"1335–umbes 1413","1335–1413":"1335–1413","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1395–Male":"1395–Surnud","1285–1340":"1285–1340","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1337":"1337","1413":"1413","1335":"1335","1453":"1453","1395":"1395","1340":"1340","1285":"1285","ABT 1413":"umbes 1413","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1340 to 1351":"1340 kuni 1351","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Hele, Devon, England":"Hele, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hele, Bradninch, Devon, England":"H